Here is your **testsmells.org 19-Smell Academic Catalog** audit for `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`.

**Framework:** MSTest 4.1.0 · **Scope:** Integration (`[TestCategory("Integration")]`) · **Test methods:** 8

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| **High** | 3 | 3 |
| **Medium** | 1 | 1 |
| Low | 0 | 0 |
| **Total** | **4** | **4** |

---

## Findings by Severity

### 🔴 HIGH 1 — Sleepy Test

**Method:** `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 82–89)

```csharp
Thread.Sleep(3000); // ← 3-second hard-coded delay
```

**Why it's a smell:** `Thread.Sleep` introduces non-deterministic timing. If the notification takes 3.1s, the test is flaky. If it takes 0.1s, you're wasting 2.9s on every run. This smell remains **High** even for integration tests — real async coordination should never rely on arbitrary sleep.

**Integration calibration:** No downgrade. Sleepy Test is a flaw regardless of test scope (Spadini et al., MSR 2020 — consistently rated serious by developers).

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay()
{
    var user = new User("dave@example.com", "Dave");
    _repository.Insert(user);

    // Poll with timeout instead of sleeping
    var timeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
    var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();
    while (sw.Elapsed < timeout)
    {
        if (_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id))
            break;
        await Task.Delay(100);
    }

    Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id),
        "Notification was not sent within the timeout period.");
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Flaky CI failures, slow test suite, unreliable signal.

---

### 🔴 HIGH 2 — Conditional Test Logic

**Method:** `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (line 93–109)

```csharp
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}
```

**Why it's a smell:** The `if/else` means one branch **never executes**. Since `Insert` creates a regular `User`, the `PremiumUser` path is dead code — giving false coverage. You can't tell from the test result which path ran.

**Integration calibration:** No downgrade. Conditional logic hides test gaps at any scope.

**Fix:** Split into two focused tests:
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_StandardUser_ReturnsCorrectName()
{
    var user = new User("eve@example.com", "Eve");
    _repository.Insert(user);

    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");

    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_PremiumUser_HasPositiveDiscount()
{
    var user = new PremiumUser("eve@example.com", "Eve", discountRate: 0.1m);
    _repository.Insert(user);

    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com") as PremiumUser;

    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.IsTrue(loaded.DiscountRate > 0);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Hidden test gap — the `PremiumUser` path is never validated.

---

### 🔴 HIGH 3 — Assertion-Free Test (Unknown Test)

**Method:** `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (line 113–119)

```csharp
public void BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }
    // ← No assertion. Passes even if every Insert silently fails.
}
```

**Why it's a smell:** The name implies "doesn't throw," but MSTest reports this as **passed** even if `Insert` silently drops every row. It provides false confidence.

**Integration calibration:** No downgrade. Assertion-free tests are always a problem.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_PersistsAllRecords()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }

    var users = _repository.ListAll();
    Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count,
        "All 100 bulk-inserted users should be persisted.");
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** False-pass — a broken `Insert` is never caught.

---

### 🟡 MEDIUM 4 — Assertion Roulette

**Method:** `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (line 28–39)

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email);
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);
// ← 4 assertions, zero messages
```

**Why it's a smell:** When one of these fails, the MSTest output says `Assert.AreEqual failed. Expected:<Alice>. Actual:<null>.` — you get the value but not *what property was being verified* or *why* it matters. With 4 bare assertions, diagnosis requires reading the source.

**Integration calibration:** Remains Medium. Message-less multi-assert patterns are a readability debt regardless of scope.

**Fix:**
```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "Inserted user should be retrievable by email.");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should round-trip through insert/load.");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should round-trip.");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Persisted user should have a positive database ID.");
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Slower triage when tests fail in CI.

